Some people argue that there is no point in preserving old buildings when land is so valuable in our cities. Others believe that old buildings are an important part of our heritage and should be preserved. Discuss both views and state your opinion.

While some argue that the value of land outweighs the importance of preserving old structures, others contend that these buildings possess historical and cultural significance that should be protected. This essay will examine both perspectives before arguing that the preservation of such structures is essential to maintaining cultural identity.

On the one hand, proponents of demolishing older buildings emphasize the economic potential of urban land. In many cities, space is scarce and demand for housing and commercial facilities is rising rapidly. Replacing outdated structures with modern developments can optimize land use and significantly increase economic returns through higher property values and business opportunities. Moreover, newly constructed buildings often incorporate advanced technologies and environmentally sustainable designs, making them more energy-efficient and better suited to contemporary needs. From this perspective, retaining older architecture may be viewed as inefficient and a barrier to urban progress.

On the other hand, preserving historic buildings plays a vital role in sustaining cultural identity and social continuity. These structures act as physical reminders of the past, showcasing architectural styles, craftsmanship, and ways of life that might otherwise be forgotten. A notable example is Hội An Ancient Town, where well-preserved buildings not only reflect centuries of history but also attract large numbers of tourists. This, in turn, generates economic benefits while reinforcing local pride. Furthermore, historic sites contribute to the distinct character of cities, preventing them from becoming visually uniform and culturally diluted in the face of globalization.

In conclusion, although redeveloping land can yield substantial economic advantages, the preservation of historic buildings is equally, if not more, important. By integrating old structures into modern urban planning, cities can achieve a balance between development and conservation, ensuring that cultural heritage is protected for future generations while still accommodating growth.
